{{Orphan|date=October 2011}}

{{unreferenced|date=July 2011}}
'''Albert Dumouchel''' (15 April 1916 <U+2013> 11 January 1971) was a Canadian artist, photographer and [[printmaker]].

==Early career==

Albert Dumouchel was born into a family of [[tradesman|tradesmen]] at Bellerive, a working-class [[parish]] in the municipality of [[Salaberry-de-Valleyfield|Valleyfield]], [[Quebec]]. He was educated at the S<U+00E9>minaire Saint Thomas D'Aquin de Valleyfield, known today as the Coll<U+00E8>ge de Valleyfield. From the age of 8, he studied violin and piano, as well as studying singing under [[Rodolphe Plamondon]]. From 1936 to 1949, he taught art classes  at the S<U+00E9>minaire de Valleyfield.

==Teaching career==

As of 1940, he acted as a [[textile design]]er at Montreal Cottons in Valleyfield. He also taught drawing, history of art, publicity and photography at the Institut des Arts graphiques which had just been founded in [[Montreal, Canada|Montreal]] (known today as [[Coll<U+00E8>ge Ahuntsic]]). He set up an engraving workshop which became famous throughout Canada, and was its artistic director for many years.

==Artistic career==

A multi-talented individual, Dumouchel was a gifted musician, photographer and painter. His overall production was immense and included more than 2,078 works created during a career lasting over thirty years.

Between 1947 and 1951, he published the series <U+201C>Cahiers des ateliers des arts graphiques<U+201D> in which can be found some of the great names in the history of art in Quebec, including [[Paul-<U+00C9>mile Borduas|Borduas]], [[Alfred Pellan|Pellan]], [[L<U+00E9>on Bellefleur|Bellefleur]], Gigu<U+00E8>re, Favreau et Mousseau.

He was an excellent photographer and participated in the activities of the Montreal [[surrealism|surrealists]]. In 1948, he signed the manifesto [[Prisme d'yeux]] and in March 1953, during an exhibition of paintings and drawings at the University of Vancouver, some sixty compositions on [[Photographic slide|slides]] were exhibited. He also took part in important manifestations around the world, including those in Paris, New York, Venice, Rio de Janeiro, [[Sao Paulo, Brazil|Sao Paulo]], Tokyo, Berlin, Milan, [[Li<U+00E8>ge, Belgium|Li<U+00E8>ge]], [[Spoleto]], [[Krak<U+00F3>w]], and [[Ottawa, Ontario|Ottawa]].

==Awards==

In 1955, Albert-Dumouchel was awarded an 18-month [[UNESCO]] [[scholarship]] to study in Europe, where he pursued his research and work on printmaking. In 1964, he was awarded membership of the [[Accademia di Belle Arti Firenze|Florentine Academy of Fine Arts]] and three years later, the Academy awarded him its centenary medal for serviced rendered to Canada. In 1967, he left his apartment/workshop in Montreal and went to live at [[Saint-Antoine-sur-Richelieu, Quebec|
 St-Antoine-sur-le-Richelieu]] where he died in 1971.

